%N A397873 Decimal expansion of the small face angle, in radians, of a canonical (dual-uniform) heptagonal trapezohedron.
%C A397873 The heptagonal trapezohedron is the dual polyhedron of the heptagonal antiprism.
%C A397873 Its faces are kites with one acute angle (this constant) and three obtuse angles (A397874).
%H A397873 Paolo Xausa, <a href="/A397873/b397873.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 0..10000</a>
%H A397873 David I. McCooey, <a href="https://dmccooey.com/polyhedra/HeptagonalTrapezohedron.html">Heptagonal Trapezohedron</a>.
%H A397873 Polytope Wiki, <a href="https://polytope.miraheze.org/wiki/Heptagonal_antitegum">Heptagonal antitegum</a>.
%H A397873 Eric Weisstein's World of Mathematics, <a href="https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Trapezohedron.html">Trapezohedron</a>.
%H A397873 <a href="/index/Tra#transcendental">Index entries for transcendental numbers</a>.
%F A397873 Equals arccos(2 - sin(Pi/14) + 3*sin(3*Pi/14) - 3*cos(Pi/7)).
%F A397873 Equals arccos(c), where c = 0.94504... is the second smallest root of 8*x^3 - 20*x^2 - 2*x + 13.
%e A397873 0.3330736914402958542342512786693373716465086742885...
%t A397873 First[RealDigits[ArcCos[Root[8*#^3 - 20*#^2 - 2*# + 13 &, 2]], 10, 100]]
%o A397873 (PARI) acos(2-sin(Pi/14)+3*sin(3*Pi/14)-3*cos(Pi/7)) \\ _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Jul 20 2026
